  "opinion": "As a retired man from Kansas City who spent his life watching birds and volunteering, I've seen the world change in ways I never anticipated. The gender gap in science, to me, isn't a simple statistic—it's the quiet moments when a girl's curiosity gets lost in the shuffle of a classroom where boys are the only ones being encouraged to ask 'why.' I remember when I was young, my parents—both educated—told me that science was for everyone, but back then, the world didn't reflect that. Today, I've seen girls in my community, especially in the science fairs I help organize, get discouraged when they don't see their peers being supported. Should we address it? Absolutely. But not with grand, top-down policies that don't consider the real-world context. Instead, we should start small: mentorship programs that pair girls with local scientists who are approachable and relatable, like the ones I've seen in my volunteer work. It's about creating spaces where girls feel safe to explore without the fear of judgment. I've noticed that when a girl is encouraged to ask questions, she becomes more confident in her abilities. The key is to make science feel personal, not abstract. I've never been on social media, so I don't know about the viral trends, but I know from my own experience that when you take time to listen and understand, real change happens. The gender gap in science is a problem that needs to be addressed, but it's not just about numbers—it's about the people who have the potential to change the world, and we need to give them the tools to do so.",
